04684nam a22007335i 9781501761584DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021011478  a97815017615847 a10.1515/97815017615842doi  a(DE-B1597)582778  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBH301.O24 7aLIT0041702bisacsh1 aFrederick, Samuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Redemption of Things :bCollecting and Dispersal in German Realism and Modernism /cSamuel Frederick. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2022  a1 online resource (348 p.) :b5 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Theorizing Collecting -- tPart I. Ephemera -- t2. Moss (Stifter) -- t3. The Photographic Instant (Fischinger) -- tPart II. Catastrophic Detritus -- t4. Divine Debris (Gotthelf) -- t5. Maculature / Zettel (Frisch) -- tPart III. Triviality -- t6. Junk and Containers (Keller) -- t7. Dust (Glauser) -- tConclusion -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCollecting is usually conceived as an activity that bestows permanence, unity, and meaning on otherwise scattered and ephemeral objects. In The Redemption of Things, Samuel Frederick emphasizes that collecting things, however, necessarily involves displacing, immobilizing, and potentially disfiguring them, too. He argues that the dispersal of objects, seemingly antithetical to the collector's task, is actually essential to the logic of gathering and preservation. Frederick locates this logic in German-language texts from the last two centuries, which witnessed a fundamental shift in our relationship to the world of things. Through analyses of collecting as a dialectical process of preservation and loss, The Redemption of Things illustrates this paradox by focusing on objects that challenge notions of collectability: ephemera, detritus, and trivialities such as moss, junk, paper scraps, dust, scent, and the transitory moment. Through readings of works by Gotthelf, Stifter, Keller, Rilke, Glauser, and Frisch, as well an experimental film by Oskar Fischinger, Frederick reveals how the difficulties posed by these fleeting, fragile, and forsaken objects reconceptualize collecting as a poetic activity that makes the world of scattered things uniquely palpable and knowable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCollectors and collecting. 0aGerman literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aObject (Aesthetics) 4aFilm & Media Studies. 4aGerman Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aCollecting in literature, literature and the ephemeral, Vilem Flusser, logic of collecting, Oskar Fischinger, Jeremias Gotthelf.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176158440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501761584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501761584/original  a978-3-11-073908-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075182-6  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK